WEBVTT

00:30.997 --> 00:35.593
- [Girl] But I'm tired!
- It's the beginning of the day now. Come on.

00:35.668 --> 00:37.829
[Girl]
All right.

00:50.550 --> 00:53.314
[Giggling]
You're it.

00:57.891 --> 00:59.825
Forward!

01:07.333 --> 01:09.665
Now hold up.

01:12.105 --> 01:15.404
The Bible says, for everything,
there is a season.

01:15.475 --> 01:17.409
And after two years
of marriage...

01:17.477 --> 01:19.570
the time has finally come
for Willie and me...

01:19.646 --> 01:22.114
to put down roots
on a ranch of our own.

01:27.020 --> 01:29.215
- So long.
- { Narrating] We left the wagon train today...

01:29.289 --> 01:32.224
and are heading out alone through
desolate and beautiful country.

01:35.528 --> 01:38.964
It's not green like the farm.
More golden.

01:40.667 --> 01:44.364
As you can tell by my handwriting,
the way is pretty bumpy.

01:44.437 --> 01:47.770
Willie's worried we got
a late start leaving Denver.

01:47.841 --> 01:51.072
August is not a good month
to start up a ranch.

01:51.144 --> 01:54.511
I did get a full year of teaching in,
and we can use the money.

01:54.581 --> 01:57.311
We also may be starting up
something else.

01:57.383 --> 02:02.320
Namely, your first grandchild.
I haven't told Willie yet.

02:02.388 --> 02:04.652
He's got so much
on his mind already.

02:04.724 --> 02:07.887
There will be plenty of time
to tell him after we've settled.

02:07.961 --> 02:10.452
For everything,
there is a season.

02:19.572 --> 02:21.597
Willie, can you pull up
for a minute?

02:30.884 --> 02:34.081
[Retching]

02:34.154 --> 02:36.714
[Coughing]

02:47.400 --> 02:49.391
Feel better?

02:50.803 --> 02:52.794
Yes.

02:52.872 --> 02:55.739
You're bound to get sick
pitching around in that wagon.

02:55.808 --> 03:00.745
There's still a couple of hours left
of daylight. We can keep going if you want.

03:00.813 --> 03:04.579
Nah, that's okay.
We'll get an early start in the morning.

03:05.885 --> 03:08.820
Come on. I'll help you
get supper started.

03:15.828 --> 03:21.266
Looks like they're alone, Trent.
Just out for a little romantic ride in the country.

03:21.334 --> 03:24.770
Shouldn't we do a roundabout,
make sure they ain't part of a wagon train?

03:24.837 --> 03:26.828
[Grunts]

03:36.816 --> 03:40.445
[Neighing]

03:49.162 --> 03:51.096
I'm tired.

03:51.164 --> 03:53.462
What I'd like'd
be a hot bath...

03:53.533 --> 03:55.467
a bottle of whiskey
and a woman.

03:55.535 --> 03:58.265
- Well, one out of three ain't bad.
- What do you say?

03:58.338 --> 04:01.136
Enough talk.

04:01.207 --> 04:03.141
Let's make me rich today.

04:12.418 --> 04:15.319
- The sodbuster ties his gun down.
- So do we.

04:15.388 --> 04:19.825
But your average rancher
don't tie his gun down, Mason.

04:24.397 --> 04:27.628
- What do you say, Trent?
- Some other time maybe.

05:19.686 --> 05:22.018
- Welcome, folks.
- Thank you, sir.

05:22.088 --> 05:25.854
Frank Taylor. Proud owner of the greatest
general store in this parts.

05:25.925 --> 05:29.383
Oh, Missie LaHaye.
And this is my husband, Willie.

05:29.462 --> 05:32.226
Pleasure. You folks
just passing through?

05:32.298 --> 05:35.699
- We're figuring on staying.
- Well, that's good news to Texford Junction.

05:37.403 --> 05:41.134
Well, if you could just show us
the land offices, Mr. Taylorson.

05:41.207 --> 05:43.266
Yes, sir.
About two doors down.

05:43.343 --> 05:45.277
Good-bye.

05:46.946 --> 05:51.076
This is the track you'll be homesteading.
Just north of McClain Place.

05:51.150 --> 05:54.608
See? There's the main creek
threading through the middle...

05:54.687 --> 05:57.019
with plenty of branches
for the cattle to water.

05:57.090 --> 06:00.253
It's a good place to start a family.
Here's the deed.

06:00.326 --> 06:03.727
I wish you folks
the very best of luck.

06:03.796 --> 06:06.094
Many come. Not many last.

06:06.165 --> 06:09.601
- We'll last.
- With hard work and a lot of prayer.

06:25.752 --> 06:27.686
[Gasps]

06:29.422 --> 06:32.357
What are you doing?

06:44.670 --> 06:49.004
Next to marrying you,
this is the happiest day of my life.

06:49.075 --> 06:52.977
- Our life.
- Missie LaHaye...

06:53.045 --> 06:56.173
as God as my witness,
I swear to work harder...

06:56.249 --> 06:58.547
than any man to build you
a home on this land.

06:58.618 --> 07:01.416
And we'll raise a family...

07:01.487 --> 07:05.150
and watch generations after generations
of LaHayes thrive and prosper.

07:06.592 --> 07:09.789
Well, Willie, I have something
to say about that.

07:09.862 --> 07:14.026
- [Chicken Clucking]
- Hey, get back here. Get back here.

07:14.100 --> 07:17.126
- Hey, hey, hey.
- I didn't see nothing, mister, honest.

07:17.203 --> 07:20.502
[Both Laughing]

07:20.573 --> 07:23.371
Chicken thieves start early
in these parts.

07:23.443 --> 07:25.377
That's the first child
I've seen.

07:25.445 --> 07:29.848
Yep. Glad you brought
all those books just for that one.

07:29.916 --> 07:31.975
I'm sure there are more.

07:34.253 --> 07:36.813
First the ranch.

07:36.889 --> 07:39.551
Then teaching.

07:39.625 --> 07:42.025
- Then everything else.
- Everything else?

07:42.094 --> 07:47.157
You know what I mean. What were you gonna
tell me before that chicken butted in?

07:47.233 --> 07:52.500
Just that, uh-
that I'm happy too, Willie.

08:03.950 --> 08:07.215
- Hello, young man.
- Howdy.

08:07.286 --> 08:10.255
I'm Missie LaHaye.
What's your name?

08:10.323 --> 08:13.087
- Jeff Huff, ma'am.
- How old are you, Jeff Huff?

08:13.159 --> 08:15.753
- Twelve years old, ma'am.
- Did you catch that chicken?

08:15.828 --> 08:19.286
No. Got distracted
by your smooching.

08:19.365 --> 08:23.131
- Sorry, ma'am.
- Well, I'm sorry we caused you
to lose your chicken.

08:23.202 --> 08:26.638
Oh. Weren't mine, anyway.
Just fooling around.

08:28.674 --> 08:31.370
[Horses Neighing]

08:57.303 --> 08:59.999
- Willie.
- Sonny! Sonny!

09:00.072 --> 09:03.235
Where you been? I been waiting
so long for you to come back.

09:03.309 --> 09:07.177
Where have you been?
Sonny? Where you been, Sonny?

09:07.246 --> 09:09.407
[Mason]
"Where you been, Sonny?"

09:09.482 --> 09:12.144
[Chuckles]

09:12.218 --> 09:14.846
- Ow.
- Leave him be. I mean it.

09:14.921 --> 09:17.481
I'm just having a little fun
with your little brother, Sonny.

09:19.659 --> 09:23.026
Why don't you and I
go in and have a drink?

09:24.730 --> 09:26.664
Sonny...

09:27.900 --> 09:29.800
you can go play.

09:40.112 --> 09:43.138
- Don't go embarrassing me like that!
- Sorry, Sonny.

09:43.215 --> 09:45.445
Got you something.

09:57.430 --> 10:01.696
Easy there, Jeff. Don't that widow feed you?
I pay her good money.

10:01.767 --> 10:05.225
I don't like it there, Sonny.
I wanna go with you.

10:05.304 --> 10:08.034
Yeah, well, you can't.

10:08.107 --> 10:10.575
I told you that
a hundred times.

10:24.857 --> 10:26.848
Whoa.

10:30.396 --> 10:33.832
I'll build you a house
a lot better than that one.

10:33.899 --> 10:37.858
Oh, no. Willie,
this house is just fine.

10:38.838 --> 10:40.669
Let's go take a look.

10:59.058 --> 11:01.253
[Missie Gasps]

11:09.502 --> 11:11.868
[Clears Throat]

11:11.937 --> 11:16.567
Humble as it may be, sweetheart, this is
the first home of our own that we've ever had.

11:23.916 --> 11:26.714
[Giggles]

11:47.707 --> 11:51.199
- No stove.
- I can use the fireplace.

11:51.277 --> 11:54.440
My cooking can't get
any worse than it is right now.

12:00.619 --> 12:04.248
Lord, bless this house
and all who enter.

12:04.323 --> 12:06.314
[Together]
Amen.

12:41.093 --> 12:45.757
Sometimes I can almost hear
your voices in the soft prairie wind.

12:59.812 --> 13:02.144
I worry about Willie.

13:02.214 --> 13:05.581
He works with a ferocity
that sometimes scares me.

13:05.651 --> 13:08.211
He's so concerned
we won't be ready for winter.

13:10.990 --> 13:14.824
I've still not found the right time
to tell him about the baby.

13:27.139 --> 13:30.199
Willie and I went riding
over our land.

13:30.276 --> 13:33.109
What a beautiful country
the Lord has made.

13:38.784 --> 13:41.412
Just the other day,
we saw Indians on our ridgeline.

13:43.689 --> 13:45.919
Willie is very concerned
for my safety...

13:45.991 --> 13:49.518
though there hasn't been any Indian attacks
in years in these parts.

14:14.486 --> 14:18.081
Willie and I are sending you a treasure map
to our hard-earned savings...

14:18.157 --> 14:21.649
which we just buried in
the wilds of our new ranch.

14:38.611 --> 14:41.444
I certainly hope
you never need to use it.

14:41.513 --> 14:44.141
Willie doesn't trust
banks out here.

14:44.216 --> 14:47.344
But then, this is
a strange and wild place.

14:52.591 --> 14:55.116
I've been punching cattle
over three years, Mr. LaHaye.

14:55.194 --> 14:58.129
I'm not as experienced as some,
but more than others.

14:58.197 --> 15:02.429
- Where you hail from, Henry?
- What does that matter? I'm here now.

15:06.305 --> 15:08.603
All right.

15:08.674 --> 15:10.938
I suppose it's none
of my business anyway.

15:11.010 --> 15:12.944
- No offense.
- None taken...

15:13.012 --> 15:16.175
if... you give me a job.

16:17.142 --> 16:19.007
How.

16:21.847 --> 16:24.577
Uh, I'm Missie LaHaye.

16:24.650 --> 16:29.178
My husband and I,
uh, homestead this place.

16:29.254 --> 16:31.279
We raise, uh, cattle.

16:33.993 --> 16:38.396
This "how," what is
that supposed to mean?

16:38.464 --> 16:40.557
You speak English?

16:40.632 --> 16:43.430
That's what they tell me.

16:43.502 --> 16:45.732
I'm Miriam Red Hawk McClain.

16:45.804 --> 16:48.034
Married to Sean McClain?

16:48.107 --> 16:51.076
We homestead the next tract
to the south of here.

16:51.143 --> 16:54.306
- Oh, we're neighbors.
- Mm-hmm. Yes, ma'am.

16:54.380 --> 16:56.940
Oh!

16:57.016 --> 16:58.950
Please. Please come in.

17:00.953 --> 17:04.513
- I don't understand, mister-
- Just Scottie's fine.

17:06.191 --> 17:08.284
Been cowboying
since I was a kid.

17:08.359 --> 17:10.294
I've done everything
there is to do.

17:10.362 --> 17:12.990
How come you haven't been hired
by one of the big outfits?

17:16.734 --> 17:21.569
I can't use this no more,
so most people think I'm washed up.

17:22.875 --> 17:26.503
But I learned
to get by with my left.

17:27.846 --> 17:31.338
You take me on, Mr. LaHaye,
and I won't let you down.

17:35.654 --> 17:38.248
You got yourself a job.

17:45.564 --> 17:50.331
Uh, I'm just getting started.
Trying to make this place into a home.

17:51.770 --> 17:53.931
Please, sit.

17:58.510 --> 18:03.140
I think I have one last jar
of strawberry preserves...

18:04.550 --> 18:08.509
that I've been saving
for just such an occasion.

18:13.392 --> 18:15.383
Please, here.

18:19.131 --> 18:22.623
Now, this here is a county fair
blue ribbon winner.

18:29.842 --> 18:32.072
Mm. Mm.

18:33.479 --> 18:35.845
This is very good. You must teach me
how to make this.

18:35.914 --> 18:40.647
Oh, my mother made it.
I'm not a very good cook.

18:40.719 --> 18:44.018
When I was growing up,
I mostly helped out my pa-

18:44.089 --> 18:48.025
riding horses, plowing the field,
tending to the chickens.

18:48.093 --> 18:50.391
Then you will do
very well here.

18:50.462 --> 18:52.396
Many women who come here
are soft.

18:52.464 --> 18:54.830
They don't know how to do
these things. You do.

18:54.900 --> 18:59.166
Still, I feel that my husband
would prefer a good meal.

19:01.306 --> 19:03.706
I brought you some things.

19:03.775 --> 19:08.007
It is too late to start a garden this year,
so corn, potatoes, beets.

19:08.080 --> 19:11.675
- Oh, thank you, Miriam.
- We are neighbors.

19:11.750 --> 19:15.846
The last family was here, well,
they could have asked us for more help...

19:15.921 --> 19:20.187
but... I think
they feared my Shoshone ways.

19:20.259 --> 19:25.663
Oh, well, my husband and I will be grateful
for whatever help we can get.

19:25.731 --> 19:27.961
Um, what is in there?

19:28.033 --> 19:32.402
- The secret to flaky biscuits.
- [Sniffs]

19:32.471 --> 19:35.099
- Pig lard.
- [Gagging]

19:35.174 --> 19:38.610
Excuse me. Sorry, sorry.

19:52.024 --> 19:55.482
- [Lowing]
- [Chattering]

19:55.561 --> 19:58.052
- What do you think about these?
- You could breed 'em.

20:03.969 --> 20:06.437
- Would you be Mr. LaHaye?
- I would.

20:06.505 --> 20:10.134
Well, I'm Fyn Anders.
I would like job, sir, if please.

20:10.209 --> 20:12.677
Uh, what kind of foreigner
is you, son?

20:12.744 --> 20:14.871
I come from Norway on boat...

20:14.947 --> 20:18.348
to find adventure
in the big, wide open spaces.

20:18.417 --> 20:20.351
Well, you have any experience
around cattle?

20:20.419 --> 20:25.356
No, sir. But I am big,
strong. Own horse.

20:25.424 --> 20:30.691
Well, Fyn Anders from Norway,
this'll be strictly trial basis.

20:32.164 --> 20:35.190
- Hope you learn fast.
- Don't worry, Mr. LaHaye.

20:35.267 --> 20:40.170
I learn good and fast.
You betcha.

20:44.076 --> 20:46.704
- What do you think?
- Probably 40 or 50-

20:46.778 --> 20:48.439
Good cow.

20:48.513 --> 20:52.108
The boys will love the jam.
And so will their pa.

20:52.184 --> 20:54.675
Sure I can't give you
any biscuits.

20:54.753 --> 20:56.448
No.

20:57.923 --> 20:59.857
Thank you, though.

20:59.925 --> 21:03.156
Well, maybe next time
I'll make them with the pig lard.

21:03.228 --> 21:05.162
[Both Laughing]

21:05.230 --> 21:07.221
If I don't retch.

21:10.435 --> 21:14.997
When you're ready to bring this little one
into the world, I will be there.

21:16.642 --> 21:20.476
- I've delivered many babies.
- Oh, Miriam, thank you!

21:35.060 --> 21:37.654
- I'll bring some books for the boys.
- Good.

21:37.729 --> 21:41.597
I don't want them growing up
illiterate like their pa.

21:41.667 --> 21:43.692
Very nice to meet you,
neighbor.

21:43.769 --> 21:45.498
You too.

21:56.815 --> 21:58.749
Here comes trouble.

22:07.292 --> 22:12.025
I, uh, heard you were
hiring some cowpokes.

22:12.097 --> 22:14.190
Jobs are filled.

22:14.266 --> 22:16.962
Oh, this is the bunch
you hired.

22:18.337 --> 22:20.601
You're really scratching
the bottom of the barrel.

22:20.672 --> 22:25.234
Too bad you just couldn't have waited
a bit, hired some real men.

22:25.310 --> 22:27.244
Just where would I find
these real men?

22:27.312 --> 22:29.212
Me.

22:29.281 --> 22:31.772
Me and my boys.

22:34.119 --> 22:37.111
Not only can we rope
and ride...

22:38.123 --> 22:41.388
but most important,
we can shoot.

22:41.460 --> 22:46.454
Hey, mister. I bet you can't
shoot worth nothing.

22:46.531 --> 22:49.591
Why don't I start with you?

22:49.668 --> 22:52.228
Trent, come on.
Let's get out of here.

22:53.505 --> 22:55.496
[Chuckles]

23:02.414 --> 23:06.851
Well, we got some cows to drive,
so watch them, and do likewise.

23:06.918 --> 23:09.045
You betcha, boss.

23:09.121 --> 23:11.055
Mr. LaHaye.

23:11.123 --> 23:14.320
How would you feel about hiring
on another broke-down old cowboy?

23:14.393 --> 23:18.124
Well, I suppose I wouldn't feel
so good about that, mister-

23:18.196 --> 23:21.188
- My name is Cookie.
- You're a cook.

23:21.266 --> 23:23.598
[Laughs]
You're real quick.

23:23.668 --> 23:25.693
Afraid I can't afford
another hand right now.

23:25.771 --> 23:28.001
Strictly on a trial basis.

23:31.076 --> 23:34.842
- [Whinnies]
- { Men Whistling, Chattering]

23:40.051 --> 23:42.986
[Cattle Lowing]

23:56.935 --> 23:59.733
[Men Chattering]

23:59.805 --> 24:03.536
Get it up there!
Move it now! Ha!

24:03.608 --> 24:06.873
It's a beautiful herd,
Willie.

24:25.063 --> 24:28.396
This way. Hyah!

24:40.946 --> 24:43.039
How do, Miss LaHaye?

24:59.297 --> 25:02.698
fills us
with such joy and pride.

25:02.767 --> 25:05.793
I can only imagine
how happy you must be.

25:05.871 --> 25:11.036
And by now, I'm sure you've shared the happy
news with that hard-working son-in-law of mine.

25:11.109 --> 25:14.476
I can still remember
the exact moment...

25:14.546 --> 25:16.707
when your mother
told me about you.

25:16.781 --> 25:19.443
I was standing in the kitchen
eating breakfast...

25:19.518 --> 25:24.922
and most of all, I remember how radiant
your mother looked when she told me.

25:27.726 --> 25:31.628
And as for you, my strong daughter,
I hope you are feeling well...

25:31.696 --> 25:35.632
and that it is
an easy pregnancy for you.

25:35.700 --> 25:38.669
I love you, darling.

25:44.676 --> 25:46.507
[Cow Roaring]

26:08.733 --> 26:10.667
My wife and my initials.

26:15.040 --> 26:17.133
Fine idea, including her.

26:17.208 --> 26:19.938
All this would be nothing
without her.

26:20.011 --> 26:24.880
Therefore, a man shall leave his father
and mother and cleave to his wife.

26:24.950 --> 26:27.180
They shall be as one.

26:27.252 --> 26:29.379
Genesis.
You know your Bible.

26:29.454 --> 26:33.948
Yes. Yes, good reading material.
Anyway, I'm happy for you.

26:34.025 --> 26:36.016
A good marriage, that's...

26:37.195 --> 26:39.129
something to be treasured.

26:39.197 --> 26:41.791
Speaking from experience?

26:44.235 --> 26:46.135
- Scottie!
- What?

26:46.204 --> 26:48.798
- Ready for another one?
- Not just yet.

26:48.873 --> 26:50.864
[Scottie]
Hold on.

26:53.812 --> 26:55.973
Where you off to?

26:56.047 --> 26:59.016
I'm taking some books
to our neighbors, the McClains.

27:00.552 --> 27:03.316
Be back in a couple
of hours.

27:13.498 --> 27:15.728
She sure is
a better rider than I am.

27:17.402 --> 27:19.427
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

27:27.245 --> 27:29.509
Buffalo.

27:29.581 --> 27:32.345
It ain't done
by white men neither.

27:32.417 --> 27:34.885
White men
only take the pelt.

27:34.953 --> 27:36.887
Injuns use just
about everything-

27:36.955 --> 27:39.719
the hide, the meat, the horns,
some of the bones.

27:39.791 --> 27:43.852
Yeah, Missie and I saw some Indians
riding south last week.

27:45.463 --> 27:47.863
All this beef is better than
this buffalo meat any day.

27:47.932 --> 27:50.730
There ain't been Injun trouble
in these parts for quite a while.

27:50.802 --> 27:52.963
Let's tell the boys.

27:55.907 --> 27:57.898
[Horse Whinnies]

28:23.568 --> 28:27.004
Lord, give this horse
wings to fly. Hyah!

28:28.039 --> 28:31.065
[Whooping]

28:43.888 --> 28:46.550
[Whooping Continues]

28:53.832 --> 28:56.164
- [Neighs]
- Fyn.

28:57.936 --> 29:00.302
Go spell Scottie. There's some sick cows
that need to be brought in.

29:00.371 --> 29:03.932
- Yes, boss.
- Mrs. LaHaye in the house?

29:04.008 --> 29:07.967
No, sir. She up and took some books
over to your neighbors...

29:08.046 --> 29:10.139
- the McClains.
- [Neighs]

29:16.187 --> 29:18.451
Boy, she sure can ride.

29:33.538 --> 29:35.529
Miriam!

29:55.560 --> 29:57.926
[Gasps]

30:00.799 --> 30:03.597
You are safe here,
Mrs. LaHaye.

30:06.237 --> 30:09.365
- I'm so sorry.
- [Speaking Native Language]

30:11.676 --> 30:13.667
You're putting a scare
into this poor woman.

30:13.745 --> 30:15.713
We were just having
a little fun.

30:15.780 --> 30:19.216
You listen to Sharp Claw!

30:20.919 --> 30:23.547
Is it trouble
you want for us?

30:24.923 --> 30:26.857
My apologies, Mrs. LaHaye.

30:28.426 --> 30:31.452
Missie, this is
my brother, Sharp Claw.

30:33.531 --> 30:37.365
I give you my word, Mrs. LaHaye,
my young hunters meant no harm...

30:37.435 --> 30:39.369
except to laugh
at your expense.

30:39.437 --> 30:42.133
Their proper behavior
when they saw you...

30:42.207 --> 30:46.735
should have been to make sure
that you arrived at your destination safely.

30:46.811 --> 30:50.144
Especially a woman
in your condition.

30:56.487 --> 30:58.079
Oh.

30:58.156 --> 31:01.319
And this is
my husband Sean.

31:04.028 --> 31:06.553
- It's a pleasure to meet you, madam.
- Nice meeting you.

31:06.631 --> 31:09.395
And Robert and Bruce.

31:09.467 --> 31:11.560
Hello, boys.

31:11.636 --> 31:13.627
Please.

31:47.906 --> 31:51.842
- Can we take our books?
- Yes, they're yours.

31:56.547 --> 32:00.176
Now, children,
these are the same books...

32:00.251 --> 32:03.482
used in almost every school
in America.

32:03.554 --> 32:05.715
Who is this McGuffey?

32:05.790 --> 32:08.520
An Ohio schoolmaster
who felt a burden from God...

32:08.593 --> 32:11.562
to teach all American children
how to read.

32:11.629 --> 32:15.690
- American children?
- Yes, sir. And that includes those...

32:15.767 --> 32:18.964
whom our late President Lincoln
called Native American.

32:20.471 --> 32:25.135
Thank you, Mrs. LaHaye.
Now, you all have your books.

32:25.209 --> 32:27.200
All you men
and children out.

32:27.278 --> 32:29.872
We have women's business
to talk about.

33:01.179 --> 33:04.171
[Laughs]
Yes.

33:20.698 --> 33:22.632
Sharp Claw!

33:25.303 --> 33:28.101
Over there.
Someone's coming.

33:35.880 --> 33:38.246
Willie.

33:38.316 --> 33:40.807
This is Miriam...

33:40.885 --> 33:44.616
and her husband, Sean,
and her brother, Sharp Claw.

33:45.957 --> 33:48.892
We're on our way
to the mountains.

33:48.960 --> 33:52.259
We intend only
to take some buffalo.

33:52.330 --> 33:56.426
I have given strict orders that no cattle are
to be harmed, and those orders will be obeyed.

34:04.509 --> 34:08.036
Mr. McClain, Mrs. McClain.

34:10.415 --> 34:13.110
Sharp Claw.

34:16.521 --> 34:20.116
- Good-bye. Thank you.
- Good-bye.

34:21.259 --> 34:23.250
Thank you.

34:39.944 --> 34:42.504
- Hold her down.
- Uh-huh.

34:42.580 --> 34:45.242
She'll be good
in a couple of weeks.

34:51.322 --> 34:55.315
- First time I ever seen 'em go on like that.
- Well.

35:07.805 --> 35:09.830
Just what did you think
you were doing, Missie?

35:09.907 --> 35:12.967
I was taking some McGuffey readers
over to the McClains.

35:13.044 --> 35:15.512
Miriam asked me to teach
her children how to read.

35:15.580 --> 35:17.707
How come you never told me
about Miriam's visit?

35:19.784 --> 35:21.752
I'm worried about you
riding alone.

35:21.819 --> 35:23.753
It's too dangerous. You won't
be doing this again, Missie.

35:23.821 --> 35:26.483
- Oh, yes, I will.!
- Oh, no, you won't.

35:26.557 --> 35:29.219
Oh, yes, I will!

35:37.602 --> 35:41.561
Missie. Sweetheart.

35:43.307 --> 35:45.707
Do you miss teaching
this much?

35:48.112 --> 35:50.546
No, that's not why
I'm crying.

35:50.615 --> 35:52.378
Then why?

35:52.450 --> 35:55.351
Because I truly believe...

35:55.419 --> 35:58.855
that the Lord sent
Miriam McClain to us.

36:00.258 --> 36:02.954
And why would he do
a thing like that?

36:04.128 --> 36:07.529
To bring our baby
into the world...

36:09.300 --> 36:12.633
healthy and hardy.

36:13.638 --> 36:15.629
Our baby?

36:21.112 --> 36:23.046
Missie.

36:23.114 --> 36:27.073
Please, Willie, don't worry.
Miriam will be my midwife.

36:27.151 --> 36:30.279
She's delivered all the babies
in her village for many years.

36:30.354 --> 36:32.219
Our baby?

36:32.290 --> 36:35.555
Oh, Willie,
aren't you happy?

36:35.626 --> 36:38.459
I'm the happiest man alive.

36:47.004 --> 36:49.837
Good grub, Cookie.

36:49.907 --> 36:53.138
- Very good.
- Perfect for a brisk night like this.

36:53.211 --> 36:55.736
Here's a blanket
to keep off the cold.

36:55.813 --> 36:58.281
Don't give her
that old horse blanket.

36:58.349 --> 37:01.341
You, uh-You take mine,
Mrs. LaHaye.

37:01.419 --> 37:05.947
Oh, no. Well, thank you both,
but I'm fine.

37:06.023 --> 37:07.923
You told them?

37:09.860 --> 37:13.421
I'd like to raise
a coffee cup to, uh-

37:13.497 --> 37:16.830
seeing as this is the strongest we got-
to Mr. And Mrs. LaHaye...

37:16.901 --> 37:18.926
and their happy news.

37:19.003 --> 37:22.598
- So say we all.
- [All] Hear! Hear!

37:22.673 --> 37:24.607
[Laughs]
Thank you.

37:31.215 --> 37:33.342
Willie.

37:33.417 --> 37:35.282
Hmm?

37:35.353 --> 37:38.322
What is it? I'm awake.

37:38.389 --> 37:42.348
They were just so kind
and concerned tonight.

37:44.195 --> 37:47.323
- The hands?
- Mm-hmm.

37:47.398 --> 37:49.389
Yep.

37:52.270 --> 37:56.036
What about their families?

37:56.107 --> 37:58.837
I really don't know
much about them.

38:00.044 --> 38:02.376
But they're good workers.

38:02.446 --> 38:06.348
And that's the most
important thing.

38:06.417 --> 38:09.580
Shouldn't we know
if they have families or not?

38:10.755 --> 38:14.054
Missie, lots of times...

38:14.125 --> 38:18.459
cowboys come out here
to get away from things.

38:19.864 --> 38:21.855
You gotta respect that.

38:24.702 --> 38:27.967
Still, it seems like
such a lonely life.

38:33.978 --> 38:37.641
- You're gonna be a wonderful mother.
- [Chuckles]

39:08.813 --> 39:11.111
So?

39:11.182 --> 39:14.083
Well, looks like they figured it
all by their lonesome.

39:15.720 --> 39:18.382
Let's make me rich today.

39:34.372 --> 39:36.806
Willie says you know
the good book.

39:36.874 --> 39:40.469
Sunday mornings, my husband
and I read the Bible and pray together.

39:40.544 --> 39:42.876
You're invited to join us.

39:42.947 --> 39:46.439
Well, thank you, Mrs. LaHaye,
but, uh, I don't think so.

39:46.517 --> 39:50.647
- Aren't you a churchgoing man?
- Actually, I used to be a preacher.

39:50.721 --> 39:54.623
- A preacher?
- Yeah, well...

39:54.692 --> 39:57.160
the Lord giveth...

39:58.496 --> 40:00.589
and the Lord taketh away.

40:02.400 --> 40:04.664
What did he take away
from you?

40:06.036 --> 40:08.027
Something very special.

40:08.105 --> 40:10.596
My wife.

40:21.719 --> 40:25.917
Fyn. Come here.

40:25.990 --> 40:28.652
- Need you to reshoe this horse.
- Yes, boss.

40:48.813 --> 40:50.747
Morning, Mrs. McClain.

40:51.749 --> 40:53.649
Mr. LaHaye.

40:58.122 --> 41:01.250
- You and Missie going into town today?
- Yes, we are.

41:02.460 --> 41:05.554
Mrs. McClain, I know
when we first met I was-

41:05.629 --> 41:09.429
Out here, neighbors need
one another, Mr. LaHaye.

41:09.500 --> 41:12.230
I couldn't agree more.

41:12.303 --> 41:15.397
- Please.
- Thank you.

41:43.167 --> 41:46.534
Basically,
you just take it up-

41:53.644 --> 41:57.444
Well, practiced lots of hours
to make it look like that.

41:57.515 --> 42:00.075
Okay, come here.
Remember how I showed you.

42:00.150 --> 42:04.052
You coil it in your left hand, like that.
Make sure there ain't no kinks in the line.

42:04.121 --> 42:06.817
This is the noose.

42:06.891 --> 42:09.553
- Okay?
- Mm-hmm.

42:09.627 --> 42:11.686
Let's see what you got.

42:15.299 --> 42:19.668
Now loosen your wrist.
When you're ready, cast it off.

42:21.972 --> 42:23.997
Oh, missed again.

42:24.074 --> 42:27.635
That's all right. Keep practicing.
I'll get another rope.

42:38.155 --> 42:40.282
I'm Missie LaHaye.

42:40.357 --> 42:42.757
He seems like a nice boy.

42:42.826 --> 42:44.760
My brother.

42:44.828 --> 42:47.956
I'm glad to hear
that he has family.

42:48.032 --> 42:51.092
- I've been a little worried about him.
- He's fine.

42:51.168 --> 42:54.194
And your mother and father?

42:55.205 --> 42:57.139
They're gone.

42:57.207 --> 42:58.765
No offense, ma'am...

42:58.842 --> 43:02.141
but it ain't your business worrying
about someone's not your kin.

43:02.212 --> 43:05.613
It's just Christian charity,
Mr. Huff.

43:09.687 --> 43:11.848
I hope we're not
interrupting you, ma'am.

43:11.922 --> 43:14.288
What do you want, Trent?

43:14.358 --> 43:17.885
I think you'd better
get saddled up.

43:17.962 --> 43:20.590
We got some riding
to do.

43:27.137 --> 43:30.538
Sonny. I did it.
I roped the post.

43:30.608 --> 43:32.940
Gotta go now.

43:33.010 --> 43:35.376
Behave yourself.
Keep practicing.

43:35.446 --> 43:39.439
- You'll be back though.
- You know it.

43:39.516 --> 43:42.212
You got my rope.

43:57.568 --> 43:59.661
Is Sonny gone a lot?

43:59.737 --> 44:02.297
It's his job.

44:02.373 --> 44:05.536
He's making money so we can have
a ranch of our own someday.

44:05.609 --> 44:08.077
He sounds like
a very good brother.

44:14.852 --> 44:17.446
[Lowing]

44:24.128 --> 44:26.062
Got yourself a strong breed.

44:26.130 --> 44:30.624
And we'll know more after roundup.
Let's call it a day.

44:39.276 --> 44:42.040
Now, children...
and Mr. McClain...

44:42.112 --> 44:46.378
I want you to write
these letters on your slates...

44:46.450 --> 44:48.475
and then sound them out.

44:48.552 --> 44:50.486
And when you know them...

44:50.554 --> 44:53.250
you'll have mastered
the entire alphabet.

44:54.591 --> 44:56.957
Help each other out now.

45:01.365 --> 45:03.925
The weather's turning cold...

45:04.001 --> 45:06.469
and Sharp Claw and his camp
will be leaving tomorrow...

45:06.537 --> 45:09.734
and you probably shouldn't
get a chill riding over.

45:09.807 --> 45:13.106
So, this is my last class
for a while?

45:13.177 --> 45:16.169
The children have learned
much from you, Mrs. LaHaye.

45:26.890 --> 45:30.155
Keep at it,
Mr. McClain.

45:30.227 --> 45:34.288
Having a turbulent time
finding a word that starts with an "X."

45:34.364 --> 45:36.298
[Chuckles]
That is a difficult letter.

45:39.870 --> 45:42.964
Well, not
for much longer.

45:47.878 --> 45:49.869
Thank you.

45:57.020 --> 45:59.147
Snow'll be coming soon.

46:00.524 --> 46:03.618
Now remember, really sound out
the words with them.

46:05.229 --> 46:08.357
And when you come back, they'll be
ready for the advanced readers.

46:08.432 --> 46:10.559
I'll keep them on it.

46:10.634 --> 46:13.102
Good.

46:13.170 --> 46:15.695
God go with you
and your family, Sharp Claw.

46:15.773 --> 46:17.900
Thank you.

46:17.975 --> 46:21.308
And, Miriam,
I'll be seeing you.

46:21.378 --> 46:23.642
Yes, you will.

46:23.714 --> 46:25.648
Safe travels.

46:25.716 --> 46:28.514
Thank you. Good-bye.

46:30.988 --> 46:32.979
[Missie]
Come on!

46:39.096 --> 46:41.496
to ensure the livestock
survive the long winter.

46:41.565 --> 46:45.399
And that over there
is gonna be all your peas.

46:45.469 --> 46:49.235
Cookie and I have prepared the soil
for a large garden next spring.

46:49.306 --> 46:52.332
I so enjoy his companionship
and his cooking.

46:52.409 --> 46:56.175
Here I just might make
a- a sweet tater patch.

46:56.246 --> 46:58.510
- Oh.
- Have large taters in here.

47:06.790 --> 47:08.655
It's all coming together.

47:08.725 --> 47:12.456
It's beginning
to feel like... home.

47:19.670 --> 47:22.833
[Men Chattering]

47:22.906 --> 47:26.398
Now, as we wait for snow, the ranch hands
have time to go into town...

47:26.476 --> 47:29.001
for some well deserved
relaxation.

47:29.079 --> 47:32.879
- This time I got a better hand-
- { Scottie] Don't tell us what you got.

47:51.068 --> 47:53.798
Maybe more now,
knowing the baby's coming.

47:58.876 --> 48:00.810
As we prepare for winter...

48:00.878 --> 48:05.645
I'm reminded of Isaiah preparing
the way for our savior's birth...

48:05.716 --> 48:09.208
and I think warmly of all of you
as Christmas approaches.

48:13.757 --> 48:16.248
[Shivering]

48:20.530 --> 48:23.090
Are you warm enough?

48:23.166 --> 48:25.157
I'm fine.

48:25.235 --> 48:28.693
Why are you always so warm?
Even your feet.

48:28.772 --> 48:31.673
Well, someone's gotta warm them
icy toes of yours.

48:31.742 --> 48:34.575
[Laughs, Sighs]

48:34.645 --> 48:36.670
I guess that's why
we're a perfect match.

48:38.382 --> 48:42.614
The sky looks like snow.
We're lucky it held off this long.

48:44.354 --> 48:46.549
You know,
I was thinking today...

48:46.623 --> 48:49.114
this is gonna be our first Christmas
in this house, Willie.

48:51.094 --> 48:55.155
I bet you miss your family and all those
family traditions you talk about.

48:56.700 --> 48:59.828
Yeah, sure, I miss them.

48:59.903 --> 49:02.098
But we'll start
new traditions here.

49:02.172 --> 49:04.367
Well, with the weather
settling in...

49:04.441 --> 49:08.070
this might be our last chance
getting to town for a while.

49:08.145 --> 49:10.477
Better tell Santa
what you want for Christmas.

49:10.547 --> 49:15.382
No, nothing store bought.
That would be just a waste of money.

49:15.452 --> 49:17.818
Well, what then?

49:19.523 --> 49:22.048
All I want for Christmas
is to be surrounded...

49:22.125 --> 49:24.992
by the people
we care about.

49:36.940 --> 49:38.999
This here's mine.

49:39.076 --> 49:41.567
No.
[Coughs]

49:43.914 --> 49:45.905
You got the watch.

49:46.950 --> 49:50.283
I got the watch...

49:50.354 --> 49:53.050
because mine broke.

49:53.123 --> 49:56.854
It's a practical thing.
I have to know the time...

49:56.927 --> 49:59.395
in order to steal.

50:00.797 --> 50:02.890
Gimme more money.

50:03.834 --> 50:06.564
No.

50:06.636 --> 50:09.127
You got two brooches
and a watch, and I don't got none of that.

50:12.809 --> 50:15.573
You ever wish you had
a place to call your own?

50:24.721 --> 50:26.951
[No Audible Dialogue]

50:28.191 --> 50:30.659
More coffee?

50:30.727 --> 50:33.389
Thank you.

50:44.841 --> 50:47.901
Mrs. LaHaye would
like to say something.

50:47.978 --> 50:51.004
Well, as you all know...

50:51.081 --> 50:53.413
Christmas will be here
before we know it.

50:53.483 --> 50:56.816
Santa Claus will never find us
all the way out here, I bet.

50:56.887 --> 51:00.653
Well, he will if my wife
has anything to say about it.

51:00.724 --> 51:05.024
Willie and I would like to cordially invite
you all to Christmas dinner.

51:07.230 --> 51:09.664
Unless you have
other places to be.

51:14.671 --> 51:18.300
Well, then that settles it.
Christmas dinner with all the trimmings.

51:18.375 --> 51:20.309
Trimmings?

51:20.377 --> 51:22.845
Now, where do you
rustle up some of those?

51:22.913 --> 51:25.711
Well, I was hoping you
might help me, Cookie.

51:34.424 --> 51:36.358
I got that.

51:36.426 --> 51:38.986
Mrs. LaHaye! Mrs. LaHaye!

51:39.062 --> 51:42.361
- Jeff. What is it?
- Mrs. LaHaye, I got something.

51:42.432 --> 51:44.195
- From Sonny.
- What's it say?

51:45.202 --> 51:48.296
Not sure.

51:48.371 --> 51:50.362
Come here.

52:02.953 --> 52:05.979
"Dear little brother,
it's real hot here.

52:06.056 --> 52:09.856
"I'll bring you some beans
that jump all by themselves.

52:09.926 --> 52:13.828
"Stay good, and I'll
see you after Christmas.

52:13.897 --> 52:15.922
Sonny."

52:19.936 --> 52:22.302
Best be going, Missie.

52:23.406 --> 52:25.704
Well, thank you,
Mrs. LaHaye.

52:39.422 --> 52:43.017
That boy's got
one speed- runnin'.

52:51.034 --> 52:54.902
I think on how long the world
lay in darkness...

52:54.971 --> 52:58.634
before the light of the world
was born in that humble little stable.

53:00.277 --> 53:03.940
We have been blessed
to receive his light.

53:04.014 --> 53:07.973
Not only to live in hope ourselves,
but to take hope to others.

53:08.051 --> 53:13.648
I am sending you something which I know
you'll remember from many Christmases past.

53:13.723 --> 53:17.284
May it start a new tradition
in the LaHaye household...

53:17.360 --> 53:20.227
and remind you
we are there in spirit...

53:20.297 --> 53:23.733
sharing your first
Christmas on the ranch.

53:23.800 --> 53:25.734
And know we will miss you...

53:25.802 --> 53:29.135
but our hearts are forever
knit together in love.

53:41.351 --> 53:44.809
Round. Take it
round there, Henry.

53:44.888 --> 53:46.856
Round. Here.

53:46.923 --> 53:50.086
Here. Fyn.
Come on, Fyn. Hurry up.

53:54.831 --> 53:58.358
I just don't understand why Willie had to
go into town on Christmas Eve.

53:58.435 --> 54:01.495
Oh, I'm sure he'll
be along shortly, ma'am.

54:08.578 --> 54:11.945
Willie LaHaye, where have you been?
It's Christmas Eve!

54:12.015 --> 54:14.040
I know.

54:14.117 --> 54:16.176
There's gonna be one more
for Christmas, Missie.

54:17.787 --> 54:19.948
Merry Christmas,
Mrs. LaHaye.

54:21.524 --> 54:24.550
Merry Christmas, Jeff.

54:30.800 --> 54:32.893
Please come in.
Come in.

54:42.712 --> 54:46.273
There's just
one thing missing.

54:56.059 --> 54:59.028
This star
stood on top...

54:59.095 --> 55:03.327
of every Christmas tree
we had when I was growing up.

55:03.400 --> 55:05.834
Go ahead.

55:08.738 --> 55:10.729
Here you go, little man.

55:12.008 --> 55:13.942
Come on.

55:38.568 --> 55:40.593
[Willie]
Oh, that was good.

55:41.705 --> 55:43.730
Mm, thank you,
Mrs. LaHaye. This is...

55:43.807 --> 55:48.107
the finest Christmas dinner
I've had in many a year.

55:48.178 --> 55:51.614
Many a year?
It's the best one I ever had.

55:53.183 --> 55:55.981
Well, thank you, but I couldn't have
done it without Cookie.

55:56.052 --> 55:58.543
Well, thank you, ma'am.

56:00.190 --> 56:02.124
Now is it time
to open presents?

56:02.192 --> 56:03.989
Presents?

56:06.663 --> 56:09.325
Yes, Jeff, I think now
it's time to open presents.

56:14.304 --> 56:16.329
All right.
Let's see.

56:16.406 --> 56:18.897
Uh, Fyn.

56:21.411 --> 56:23.811
Scottie.

56:25.849 --> 56:27.783
Henry.

56:29.319 --> 56:33.016
And Je-
Oh, me.

56:33.089 --> 56:35.580
And Cookie.
Here ya go.

56:36.760 --> 56:38.694
Well, go ahead.
Open 'em up.

56:43.733 --> 56:45.667
Oh.

56:58.715 --> 57:01.013
Thank you, Mrs. LaHaye.

57:02.719 --> 57:05.313
This is the best Christmas
I ever had.

57:05.388 --> 57:07.379
Me too.

57:09.526 --> 57:11.494
What is it, Scottie?

57:11.561 --> 57:13.529
This is the...

57:13.596 --> 57:16.030
first Christmas
present I ever got.

57:24.507 --> 57:29.706
Well, gentlemen, I know how you all
feel about Bible reading...

57:29.779 --> 57:32.304
but it wouldn't be
Christmas without it.

57:32.382 --> 57:35.146
So, you are welcome to stay,
but if you want to leave-

57:35.218 --> 57:38.847
l- I believe I'd
like to stay, ma'am.

57:38.922 --> 57:41.891
Yeah, I'd like to stay too.

57:41.958 --> 57:44.051
Me too, ma'am.

57:50.500 --> 57:52.434
Gospel,
according to Luke?

58:01.578 --> 58:04.046
"And so...

58:04.113 --> 58:06.047
"Joseph went up
from Galilee...

58:06.115 --> 58:08.549
"to the city of Nazareth,
to Judaea...

58:08.618 --> 58:11.348
"to be enrolled with Mary,
his betrothed...

58:11.421 --> 58:13.389
"who was with child.

58:13.456 --> 58:17.187
"And while they were there,
the time came for her to be delivered.

58:17.260 --> 58:19.728
"And she gave birth
to her firstborn son.

58:19.796 --> 58:23.789
"And she wrapped him in swaddling clothes,
and laid him in a manger.

58:23.867 --> 58:26.199
"And an angel of the Lord
appeared above them...

58:26.269 --> 58:28.635
"and the glory of the Lord
shone around them...

58:28.705 --> 58:31.367
"and they were
filled with fear.

58:31.441 --> 58:33.432
"And the angel said to them...

58:33.510 --> 58:35.808
""Be not afraid,
for behold...

58:35.879 --> 58:38.074
""I bring you good news
of a great joy...

58:38.147 --> 58:40.138
""which will come to
all the people.

58:40.216 --> 58:44.414
""For unto you this day is born,
in the city of David...

58:44.487 --> 58:48.048
the savior
who is Christ, the Lord."

58:48.124 --> 58:50.285
- Amen.
- Amen.
- Amen.

58:50.360 --> 58:51.657
- Amen.
- Amen.

58:51.728 --> 58:54.060
Amen.

59:28.831 --> 59:30.765
How.

59:33.136 --> 59:35.104
I've missed you, neighbor.

59:35.171 --> 59:38.004
I missed you too.

59:56.993 --> 59:59.154
Sonny.! Sonny.!

01:00:04.467 --> 01:00:06.401
Oh, now,
isn't that sweet?

01:00:06.469 --> 01:00:09.233
Is there nothing good
and decent with you guys?

01:00:09.305 --> 01:00:11.637
Hey, Mason, come on.

01:00:11.708 --> 01:00:14.199
Let's give them
some privacy.

01:00:14.277 --> 01:00:16.643
Oh, well, that's just
real nice of you, Trent.

01:00:21.684 --> 01:00:23.879
- Come here.
- How's it goin'?

01:00:23.953 --> 01:00:27.787
Oh, l- I really got a lot of stuff
to tell you about.

01:00:27.857 --> 01:00:31.384
Um, it's kinda hard
to know where to start.

01:00:43.573 --> 01:00:46.201
As long as the old man
don't blow it.

01:00:49.178 --> 01:00:51.112
Mind if I sit in?

01:00:52.615 --> 01:00:55.413
Uh, we're just about to leave.
Uh, I'm out.

01:00:55.485 --> 01:00:57.646
Oh, come on, Scottie.
Just a few more hands.

01:00:57.720 --> 01:00:59.745
I can win it all back.
I feel it.

01:00:59.822 --> 01:01:02.086
Uh, let's go, Fyn. You're almost
out of money anyway.

01:01:02.158 --> 01:01:04.752
- LaHayes doesn't pay you.
- Well, like all cowboys...

01:01:04.827 --> 01:01:07.625
we get paid
when the cattle is sold.

01:01:07.697 --> 01:01:10.928
No, no, no.
Mr. LaHaye pay us anyway.

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:14.902
He dig up a tin of
dollar bills just to pay us.

01:01:14.971 --> 01:01:17.769
It's like a-
a buried treasure.

01:01:17.840 --> 01:01:20.070
Don't listen to him. He's drunk.
Now come on, Fyn!

01:01:26.883 --> 01:01:29.078
[Chuckles]

01:01:29.152 --> 01:01:31.143
Just like buried treasure.

01:01:51.107 --> 01:01:54.076
Old Henry's going to
Sunday morning meeting.

01:01:54.143 --> 01:01:56.737
Well, maybe I should
be going too.

01:01:58.147 --> 01:02:03.210
If believin' the way they does
makes them the way they is...

01:02:03.286 --> 01:02:05.345
it bides
looking into sometime.

01:02:09.659 --> 01:02:14.028
Henry, will you be so kind
as to lead us in prayer?

01:02:15.631 --> 01:02:17.599
I don't know, ma'am. I'm-

01:02:17.667 --> 01:02:20.192
I'm afraid I'm
out of practice.

01:02:21.270 --> 01:02:24.899
Kind of-
Kind of hard to...

01:02:24.974 --> 01:02:27.169
start.

01:02:27.243 --> 01:02:30.212
It's okay to stumble.

01:02:30.279 --> 01:02:32.213
He's ready to catch you.

01:02:40.790 --> 01:02:42.724
[Clears Throat]

01:02:42.792 --> 01:02:46.785
Lord, sometimes...

01:02:46.863 --> 01:02:50.993
we look
but don't perceive.

01:02:53.870 --> 01:02:58.068
Sometimes we listen
but don't understand.

01:02:58.141 --> 01:03:02.305
Please, open our ears
and eyes...

01:03:02.378 --> 01:03:04.369
to your truth.

01:03:05.748 --> 01:03:07.739
- Amen.
- Amen.

01:03:07.817 --> 01:03:10.217
- Amen.
- { Knocking]

01:03:10.286 --> 01:03:13.050
It's open to
everyone on Sunday.

01:03:15.892 --> 01:03:19.350
Oh, Fyn. Oh, I'm so happy to see you.
Please come in.

01:03:26.936 --> 01:03:30.064
Sorry, boss.
He got the jump on me.

01:03:30.139 --> 01:03:32.266
- What do you want?
- I want your money.

01:03:33.776 --> 01:03:35.607
Let's go.
Follow him.

01:03:35.678 --> 01:03:37.646
Get up.
Move it out.

01:03:39.282 --> 01:03:42.251
Hey, there, come on.!

01:03:42.318 --> 01:03:44.684
Let's go.
Come on.

01:03:44.754 --> 01:03:47.746
Come on. Come on.
Good Sunday morning to y'all.

01:04:01.504 --> 01:04:03.438
Sonny?

01:04:07.944 --> 01:04:10.811
Jeff, l- I didn't know.
I thought you was in town.

01:04:10.880 --> 01:04:13.110
What ya doing?

01:04:14.717 --> 01:04:16.776
Ain't this sweet?

01:04:16.853 --> 01:04:20.050
All right,
all of you, sit down.

01:04:20.122 --> 01:04:22.215
Come on.

01:04:25.127 --> 01:04:27.152
You too, kid.

01:04:27.230 --> 01:04:29.494
Just do as the man says.

01:04:34.003 --> 01:04:37.131
I'll just go over
and get my treasure map.

01:04:37.206 --> 01:04:38.798
Leave her alone!

01:04:39.742 --> 01:04:41.300
Now...

01:04:41.377 --> 01:04:44.744
I missed on purpose,
but I won't do it twice.

01:04:44.814 --> 01:04:46.782
Please. You can see
she's expecting.

01:04:46.849 --> 01:04:48.783
So am I.

01:04:48.851 --> 01:04:51.649
I'm expecting to come back here
with more money than I left with.

01:04:53.256 --> 01:04:55.451
I don't know what makes you
think that there's any money.

01:04:55.524 --> 01:04:59.517
Well, your Norwegian cowpoke...

01:04:59.595 --> 01:05:03.531
has a tendency to run off at the mouth
after a couple of pints.

01:05:03.599 --> 01:05:06.090
Showing off his money,
and bragging about...

01:05:06.168 --> 01:05:09.831
how his boss has a treasure
buried on his land.

01:05:09.906 --> 01:05:12.272
Tie him up.

01:05:17.613 --> 01:05:20.514
You do as he says, Missie,
you'll be all right.

01:05:20.583 --> 01:05:23.143
You remember where
we dug that hole?

01:05:23.219 --> 01:05:26.279
- I think I remember.
- You'll be fine.

01:05:29.025 --> 01:05:31.186
All right.
Enough said.

01:05:31.260 --> 01:05:33.285
Let's make me rich today.

01:05:33.362 --> 01:05:35.330
Hyah.!

01:05:48.811 --> 01:05:50.802
Hurry it up.

01:05:50.880 --> 01:05:54.247
- I need something to dig with.
- Well, then use your hands.

01:05:54.317 --> 01:05:56.478
Make it quick.

01:06:06.929 --> 01:06:09.454
Is that it or not?

01:06:11.000 --> 01:06:13.560
Well, then toss it over.

01:06:36.492 --> 01:06:39.393
You're gonna have to show me where
the rest of the money is.

01:06:39.462 --> 01:06:42.954
But y-you have all the money.
There is no more.

01:06:43.032 --> 01:06:45.500
No, I don't have
all the money.

01:06:45.568 --> 01:06:49.732
'Cause that Norwegian,
he wasn't spending silver.

01:06:49.805 --> 01:06:52.239
He was spending cash.

01:07:02.018 --> 01:07:05.112
I could just about eat me
a whole side of beef right now.

01:07:05.187 --> 01:07:09.624
Well, if you turn me loose,
I'll cook you whatever you want.

01:07:09.692 --> 01:07:12.957
- Like rat stew.
- Oh, and now how stupid you think I am?

01:07:13.029 --> 01:07:15.554
You're working for Trent,
ain't you?

01:07:15.631 --> 01:07:17.963
Equal partners is what we is.

01:07:18.034 --> 01:07:20.002
That right, Sonny?

01:07:20.069 --> 01:07:22.731
You equal partners
with these lowlifes?

01:07:22.805 --> 01:07:25.501
Shut your mouth!

01:07:27.209 --> 01:07:29.905
[Chuckles]
Ooh.

01:07:29.979 --> 01:07:31.810
Why don't you tell
your brother, Sonny?

01:07:33.482 --> 01:07:36.246
Why don't you tell him what
you do to make money?

01:07:36.318 --> 01:07:38.582
Tell him how all you do
is rob innocent people.

01:07:38.654 --> 01:07:40.588
Probably been involved
in a murder or two.

01:07:40.656 --> 01:07:42.453
That's a lie!

01:07:42.525 --> 01:07:45.585
Tell him he's wrong, Sonny.
You ain't never killed nobody.

01:07:45.661 --> 01:07:49.495
Tell him, Sonny. Tell-Tell him
you ain't like these other bad men.

01:07:50.666 --> 01:07:54.261
I ain't never
killed nobody. Never.

01:07:57.873 --> 01:08:01.036
Don't you see?

01:08:01.110 --> 01:08:03.578
I'm doing this
for us, Jeff.

01:08:03.646 --> 01:08:06.342
Our future. You and me
and the life we're trying to have.

01:08:06.415 --> 01:08:10.146
No, Sonny.
You can't mean that.

01:08:10.219 --> 01:08:12.517
What would Ma and Pa say
about your thieving ways?

01:08:12.588 --> 01:08:14.647
They'd say,
"Good for you, Sonny.

01:08:14.723 --> 01:08:17.953
Trying to make a life for
you and your little brother. '"

01:08:18.027 --> 01:08:20.086
So you think...

01:08:20.162 --> 01:08:23.689
they're looking down from heaven
right now, and they're proud of you?

01:08:23.765 --> 01:08:26.758
Aren't you tired of living
in that boardinghouse?

01:08:26.836 --> 01:08:30.703
Huh? No place
that's really yours?

01:08:30.773 --> 01:08:32.741
I want a better life
for us, Jeff.

01:08:32.808 --> 01:08:34.832
That's why I'm doing this.

01:08:34.910 --> 01:08:37.935
These folks are
my friends, Sonny.

01:08:38.013 --> 01:08:40.379
Mrs. LaHaye been
teaching me to read.

01:08:40.448 --> 01:08:44.145
Mr. LaHaye fetches me for the Sunday
meetings, and he's teaching me ranching.

01:08:44.220 --> 01:08:48.953
These are the kind of people things always
work out for. They'll be fine.

01:08:49.024 --> 01:08:52.255
We ain't taking nothing from them
they can't get back 10 times over.

01:08:56.932 --> 01:09:00.662
When this is over, you and me
can spend all the time you want together.

01:09:22.191 --> 01:09:25.024
Get it out of there.

01:09:30.633 --> 01:09:32.863
Toss it to me.

01:09:51.819 --> 01:09:54.812
- You got a key for this?
- No.

01:09:59.762 --> 01:10:02.993
Don't you trust
nobody anymore?

01:10:08.137 --> 01:10:13.131
Oh, my,
isn't that pretty?

01:10:13.209 --> 01:10:15.336
- Whoo-wee.
- { Gun Cocks]

01:10:15.411 --> 01:10:17.140
Put your hands in the air.

01:10:19.715 --> 01:10:21.649
You know how to use that?

01:10:26.922 --> 01:10:29.652
I missed on purpose.

01:10:29.725 --> 01:10:31.989
I won't do it twice.

01:10:32.061 --> 01:10:34.325
Shooting a man's
a different story.

01:10:34.396 --> 01:10:38.162
A good Christian woman
like yourself wouldn't hurt anyone.

01:10:38.234 --> 01:10:40.202
So what you gonna do?

01:10:49.211 --> 01:10:51.543
That's two more shots.

01:10:55.117 --> 01:10:57.551
- [Yells]
- [Grunts]

01:11:24.213 --> 01:11:26.147
This is for your own good.

01:11:35.457 --> 01:11:38.187
Look.

01:11:39.461 --> 01:11:42.055
Where's the woman, Trent?
What did you do?

01:11:42.131 --> 01:11:43.758
Mi-

01:11:43.832 --> 01:11:46.027
Where is she?
Go get her! Go find her!

01:11:46.101 --> 01:11:48.865
- What are you doing here?
- It's all right, Jeff. I will. I will.

01:11:48.937 --> 01:11:51.030
- Get her.
- Jeff, it's all right.

01:11:51.106 --> 01:11:53.404
Listen to me.
Listen to me. I will, Jeff.

01:11:53.475 --> 01:11:55.670
What'd you do with that girl?
Where is she?

01:11:55.744 --> 01:11:58.508
It's all right.
It's all right, Jeff.

01:11:58.580 --> 01:12:00.605
It's all right.
Where is she, Trent?

01:12:00.683 --> 01:12:05.052
You'd better tell me
she ain't hurt, or so help me.

01:12:13.862 --> 01:12:16.353
Drop your gun, Sonny,
or he's dead.

01:12:16.432 --> 01:12:18.457
Missie.

01:12:19.668 --> 01:12:22.364
- Missie?
- Sonny, go cut Willie loose...

01:12:22.438 --> 01:12:24.406
and don't you
so much as nick him.

01:12:29.978 --> 01:12:34.312
Find it hard to believe
you got the drop on Trent.

01:12:34.383 --> 01:12:36.647
I got his gun
and his dignity.

01:12:50.299 --> 01:12:53.393
Missie, pick up the gun,
and move away from him.

01:13:04.747 --> 01:13:06.840
Looks like you got me.

01:13:06.915 --> 01:13:11.181
Sonny, tie him up.
Just like you did us.

01:13:11.253 --> 01:13:14.017
Then maybe we'll ask
the law to spare your life.

01:13:19.027 --> 01:13:20.961
Here, let me help you
with that, Sonny.

01:13:26.268 --> 01:13:28.031
Sonny!

01:13:33.342 --> 01:13:35.776
[Wheezing]

01:13:35.844 --> 01:13:38.108
It's okay.
Just don't go away, Sonny.

01:13:38.180 --> 01:13:40.114
Don't go.

01:13:40.182 --> 01:13:42.047
Don't go away.

01:13:43.285 --> 01:13:46.186
Fix him up, won't ya?
He wouldn't have hurt ya.

01:13:46.255 --> 01:13:49.622
Oh, I would fix him if I could.
I knew he wouldn't hurt me.

01:13:53.562 --> 01:13:56.122
I'm so sorry for
what I done, ma'am.

01:13:56.198 --> 01:13:58.132
Please forgive me.

01:13:58.200 --> 01:14:01.499
Don't hold my deeds
against him.

01:14:01.570 --> 01:14:03.538
He's got no one now.

01:14:03.605 --> 01:14:05.971
He's got nobody.

01:14:06.041 --> 01:14:08.373
Oh, no, forgiveness
is yours, Sonny.

01:14:08.444 --> 01:14:10.742
He'll be with us now,
I promise.

01:14:19.321 --> 01:14:21.380
You grow up to be a man...

01:14:21.457 --> 01:14:25.757
that Pa would be proud of,
you hear me, Jeff?

01:14:25.828 --> 01:14:28.422
I will.

01:14:28.497 --> 01:14:33.332
And you promise me you won't
spend your days missing me.

01:14:33.402 --> 01:14:35.768
Ask me no questions...

01:14:35.838 --> 01:14:37.931
I'll tell you no lies.

01:14:42.311 --> 01:14:44.575
I'll pray for you, Sonny.

01:14:44.646 --> 01:14:47.046
Now, don't go wasting
your prayers on me, ma'am.

01:14:49.818 --> 01:14:53.686
I done too many bad things
for God to be forgivin'.

01:14:53.755 --> 01:14:56.747
Long ago,
there was a thief...

01:14:56.825 --> 01:14:59.055
left on a cross to die,
just like you, Sonny.

01:14:59.127 --> 01:15:05.088
But then he heard the glorious words
of the Lord about redemption.

01:15:05.167 --> 01:15:08.193
And he knew that very day
he was gonna be in paradise.

01:15:10.138 --> 01:15:12.606
He's waiting
for you, Sonny.

01:15:14.209 --> 01:15:16.143
Go with God.

01:15:55.284 --> 01:16:00.620
"Thou anointest my head with oil,
and my cup runneth over.

01:16:00.689 --> 01:16:03.180
"Surely, goodness and mercy...

01:16:03.258 --> 01:16:07.490
"shall follow me
all the days of my life-

01:16:07.563 --> 01:16:12.091
and I will dwell in
the house of the Lord forever. '"

01:16:12.167 --> 01:16:14.328
Amen.

01:16:32.754 --> 01:16:36.383
Jeff's part of
our family now.

01:16:37.626 --> 01:16:40.459
Yep.

01:16:40.529 --> 01:16:42.861
If someday he wants to
take the LaHaye name...

01:16:44.533 --> 01:16:46.592
I'd be fine
with that too.

01:16:49.204 --> 01:16:51.195
That would
be nice, Willie.

01:16:57.212 --> 01:17:00.545
We are gonna need
a bigger house.

01:17:00.616 --> 01:17:03.050
I was thinking I could
knock out this back wall...

01:17:03.118 --> 01:17:05.086
maybe put in
a bedroom or two.

01:17:05.153 --> 01:17:07.087
- Maybe-
- [Inhales] Willie.

01:17:10.626 --> 01:17:14.528
- Yeah?
- I think maybe you should put your boots back on.

01:17:17.065 --> 01:17:18.828
It's time.

01:17:18.900 --> 01:17:21.892
But Miriam said we were
still a few weeks away.

01:17:21.970 --> 01:17:24.666
No, I think you'd best
be getting Miriam.

01:17:24.740 --> 01:17:27.038
Now.

01:17:27.109 --> 01:17:29.043
What's the matter?

01:17:30.979 --> 01:17:35.109
You're gonna sleep in the bunkhouse
tonight, Jeff, just like a real cowboy.

01:17:36.818 --> 01:17:38.513
I'm having the baby.

01:17:58.674 --> 01:18:00.869
Maybe I'll go, uh,
check on those cattle.

01:18:02.477 --> 01:18:05.037
Okay, sure.

01:18:05.113 --> 01:18:07.206
I'll go with you.

01:18:07.282 --> 01:18:09.807
Uh, maybe I'll wait
a little bit.

01:18:11.186 --> 01:18:13.654
Okay.

01:18:13.722 --> 01:18:15.485
Yeah, I'll wait.

01:18:15.557 --> 01:18:18.492
It ain't your firstborn
you're worrying about.

01:18:18.560 --> 01:18:21.051
Now quit it.
You're making the boss crazy.

01:18:25.367 --> 01:18:27.631
It's gotten
awfully quiet in there.

01:18:46.021 --> 01:18:49.479
- It's a boy!
- [Cheering]

01:18:50.559 --> 01:18:52.493
Willie.

01:18:54.730 --> 01:18:56.925
Come and meet your son.

01:19:23.125 --> 01:19:26.356
We never did get around
to deciding what to name him.

01:19:26.428 --> 01:19:29.226
I was thinking...

01:19:29.297 --> 01:19:31.231
"Matthew."

01:19:31.299 --> 01:19:33.290
After your brother.

01:19:34.436 --> 01:19:38.031
Matthew Isaiah LaHaye.

01:19:40.909 --> 01:19:42.843
Mattie.

01:19:45.113 --> 01:19:47.081
It fits.

01:19:55.891 --> 01:19:58.018
Shoo. Shoo.

01:19:58.093 --> 01:20:00.152
She needs her rest.

01:20:00.228 --> 01:20:02.162
It's all right, Miriam.

01:20:02.230 --> 01:20:04.164
You can come closer.

01:20:22.317 --> 01:20:24.251
Hello.

01:20:26.688 --> 01:20:29.919
we had finally reached
the end of our journey.

01:20:29.991 --> 01:20:34.257
But now I know that the journeys
long and lasts a lifetime.

01:20:34.329 --> 01:20:36.923
Each day on the ranch,
I am reminded of God's plan...

01:20:36.998 --> 01:20:39.660
and the never ending
circle of life.

01:20:59.487 --> 01:21:01.421
I love you.

01:21:03.825 --> 01:21:05.759
Bye, Willie.

01:21:18.573 --> 01:21:20.768
Matthew has your eyes...

01:21:23.712 --> 01:21:26.613
{ Missie Narrating]Jeff has thrived,
and Willie and I are very proud...

01:21:26.681 --> 01:21:29.479
he has taken
the name of LaHaye.

01:21:29.551 --> 01:21:32.179
Bye-bye, Scottie.

01:21:45.066 --> 01:21:48.968
You take care, Mrs. LaHaye.
We'll be back pretty soon now.

01:21:49.037 --> 01:21:51.801
- See you, Cookie.
- Take care.

01:21:51.873 --> 01:21:53.670
Safe travels.

01:21:57.045 --> 01:22:00.503
and Willie and the ranch hands
are driving some of them to the market.

01:22:11.893 --> 01:22:14.657
Whoa.
Look at this one.

01:22:14.729 --> 01:22:16.959
- Oh, wow.
- This is huge.

01:22:19.167 --> 01:22:21.192
- Will you bring it in?
- Okay.

01:22:24.139 --> 01:22:26.073
to put up
for the winter.

01:22:26.141 --> 01:22:28.666
Who knows what
the next year will bring.

01:22:28.743 --> 01:22:33.009
I am confdent the love of God
and family will light our path.

01:22:33.081 --> 01:22:35.413
And a renewed faith
in the words...

01:22:35.483 --> 01:22:37.815
"For everything,
there is a season...

01:22:37.886 --> 01:22:41.754
and a time for
every matter under heaven. '"
